"Gardner J.L., Heinsohn R., Joseph L.","Shifting latitudinal clines in avian body size correlate with global warming in Australian passerines",2009,"Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences","276","1674",,"3845","3852",,,10.1098/rspb.2009.1011,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-72449185276&partnerID=40&md5=fc6fe2c7ef8f6c51023ec3673a4799af","Department of Botany and Zoology, Research School of Biology, Australian National University, Canberra, ACT 0200, Australia; Fenner School of Environment and Society, Australian National University, Canberra, ACT 0200, Australia; Australian National Wildlife Collection, CSIRO Sustainable Ecosystems, GPO Box 284, Canberra, ACT 2601, Australia","Gardner, J.L., Department of Botany and Zoology, Research School of Biology, Australian National University, Canberra, ACT 0200, Australia; Heinsohn, R., Fenner School of Environment and Society, Australian National University, Canberra, ACT 0200, Australia; Joseph, L., Australian National Wildlife Collection, CSIRO Sustainable Ecosystems, GPO Box 284, Canberra, ACT 2601, Australia","Intraspecific latitudinal clines in the body size of terrestrial vertebrates, where members of the same species are larger at higher latitudes, are widely interpreted as evidence for natural selection and adaptation to local climate. These clines are predicted to shift in response to climate change. We used museum specimens to measure changes in the body size of eight passerine bird species from south-eastern Australia over approximately the last 100 years. Four species showed significant decreases in body size (1.8-3.6% of wing length) and a shift in latitudinal cline over that period, and a meta-analysis demonstrated a consistent trend across all eight species. Southern high-latitude populations now display the body sizes typical of more northern populations pre-1950, equivalent to a 7° shift in latitude. Using ptilochronology, we found no evidence that these morphological changes were a plastic response to changes in nutrition, a likely non-genetic mechanism for the pattern observed. Our results demonstrate a generalized response by eight avian species to some major environmental change over the last 100 years or so, probably global warming. © 2009 The Royal Society.","Adaptation; Bergmann's rule; Climate change; Meta-analysis; Phenotypic plasticity; Ptilochronology","adaptation; Bergmann Rule; body size; chronology; climate change; cline; latitudinal gradient; meta-analysis; natural selection; passerine; phenotypic plasticity; temporal period; article; Australia; body size; body weight; climate change; controlled study; environmental change; greenhouse effect; latitude; morphology; nonhuman; nutrition; population structure; priority journal; songbird; species difference; Aves; Passeriformes; Vertebrata",,,,,,"Baker, A.J., Morphometric differentiation in New Zealand populations of the house sparrow (Passer domesticus) (1980) Evolution, 34, pp. 638-653. , doi:10.2307/2408018; Bergmann, C., Über die verhältnisse der warmeokonomiedie thiere zu ihrer grösse (1847) Göttinger Studien, 3, pp. 595-708; Blem, C., Avian energy storage (1990) Curr. Ornith., 7, pp. 59-113; Brown, W.L., Wilson, E.O., Character displacement (1956) Syst. Zool., 5, pp. 49-64. , doi:10.2307/2411924; Burke, D.M., Nol, E., Influence of food abundance, nest-site habitat, and forest fragmentation on breeding Ovenbirds (1998) Auk, 115 (1), pp. 96-104; Collins, D., Annual temperature summary - Australia records warmest decade (2000) Climate Change Newslett., 12, p. 6; Dayan, T., Simberloff, D., Size patterns among competitors: Ecological character displacement and character release in mammals, with special reference to island populations (1998) Mammal. Rev., 28, pp. 99-124. , doi:10.1046/j.1365-2907.1998.00029.x; Dewitt, T.J., Sih, A., Wilson, D.S., Costs and limits of phenotypic plasticity (1998) Trends Ecol. Evol., 13, pp. 77-81. , doi:10.1016/S0169-5347(97)01274-3; Doherty,